    "creation_date" : 1333095792,
    "answer_id" : 9939359,
    "question_id" : 740299,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Always safe to use either Comparator or Comparable interface to provide sorting implementation (if the object is not a String or Wrapper classes for primitive data types) . \nAs an example for a comparator implementation to sort employees based on name</p>\n\n<pre><code>    List&lt;Employees&gt; empList = new LinkedList&lt;Employees&gt;(EmpSet);\n\n    class EmployeeComparator implements Comparator&lt;Employee&gt; {\n\n            public int compare(Employee e1, Employee e2) {\n                return e1.getName().compareTo(e2.getName());\n            }\n\n        }\n\n   Collections.sort(empList , new EmployeeComparator ());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Comparator is useful when you need to have different sorting algorithm on same object (Say emp name, emp salary, etc). Single mode sorting can be implemented by using Comparable interface in to the required object.</p>\n"
  }, {
